cs.CV, cs.RO, cs.SI, cs.LG, cs.MM 

This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with tracking pedestrians in crowded scenes using particle filtering and motion models. It may also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as tracking pedestrians is an important task for autonomous robots. The paper also involves optimization and parameter estimation, which could place it in the statistical learning (cs.LG) and signal processing (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the use of video datasets suggests that it could also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
